@endnode
@node oBuildDirInfoA "OpenUtil.library / File Operations / oBuildDirInfoA()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oBuildDirInfoA       -- create directory tree information
        oBuildDirInfo        -- varargs stub for oBuildDirInfoA()

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oBuildDirInfoA (DirLock, Tags)
                           A0     A1

        oBuildDirInfo  (DirLock, FirstTag, ...)

        struct oDirInfo * oBuildDirInfoA (BPTR, struct TagItem *)

        struct oDirInfo * oBuildDirInfo  (BPTR, Tag, ...)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        oBuildDirInfoA() creates a structure which contains information about
        how many files, dirs & bytes are stored in the passed directory.
        Optional, a full directory tree can be created.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        DirLock    - A directory Lock, shared or exclusive.

        Tags       - The following Tags may be passed:

            oBDI_BuildDirTree

                BOOL. If TRUE, oBuildDirInfoA() builds a directory tree,
                which is stored in the DirTree field of the returned oDirInfo
                structure. For more information about the oDirInfo & oDirEntry
                structures please refer to include:libraries/OpenUtil.h.
                Default: FALSE (don't build DirTree).

            oBDI_MatchAny

                STRPTR. Only entries which contain the passed string at any
                position get added to the oDirInfo file & byte counts, and
                (if used) to the DirTree.

            oBDI_MatchBegin

                STRPTR. Only entries which begin with the passed string
                get added to the oDirInfo file & byte counts, and (if used)
                to the DirTree.

            oBDI_MatchEnd

                STRPTR. Only entries which end with the passed string
                get added to the oDirInfo file & byte counts, and (if used)
                to the DirTree.

            oBDI_MatchExact

                STRPTR. Only entries of the specified name get added to the
                oDirInfo file & byte counts, and (if used) to the DirTree.

            oBDI_MatchPattern

                STRPTR. A file pattern string may be passed here, which affects
                both the oDirEntry info and (if oBDI_BuildDirTree is set) the
                DirTree. Entries which do not match the pattern get skipped.
                Provide 2 KB Stack space when using a pattern; especially when
                scanning dirs recursively.

            oBDI_CaseSensitive

                BOOL. Used together with one of the oBDI_MatchXxx Tags for file
                name filtering. If TRUE, match is case-sensitive. Default: FALSE.

            oBDI_Recursive

                BOOL. If TRUE, the passed directory is scanned recursively with
                all sub-dirs & files, else only the contents of the passed
                directory itself get processed, which affects the ByteCount,
                FileCount, DirCount and DirTree fields of the returned oDirInfo
                structure. Default: FALSE (no recursion).

            oBDI_ScanInfoHook

                struct Hook *. This one points to a Hook which receives the name
                of the directory which is currently scanned. Useful when scanning
                a high-level directory with tons of entries to show up that your
                application is still alive and working. You may also use the Hook
                for aborting the scan. If your ScanInfoHook returns FALSE (abort),
                oBuildDirInfoA() sets IoErr to ERROR_BREAK. If you're also using
                an Error Hook, note that a user break also calls the Error Hook.

                Hook example (as defined in include:utility/hooks.h):

                ULONG __saveds __asm ScanInfoHookEntry (register __a0 struct Hook * hook,
                                                        register __a2 APTR          object,
                                                        register __a1 APTR          message);
                {
                  Printf("%s\n", object);

                  if (UserHasAborted)
                  {
                    return(FALSE);      // Stop
                  }
                  return(TRUE);         // Continue
                }

                If oBDI_Recursive isn't set, the ScanInfo Hook is only called once.

            oBDI_ErrorHook

                struct Hook *. This is a pointer to a Hook which is called if
                an error occurs. If the error is of fatal type (bad parameters,
                out of memory etc.), the Error Hook isn't called. Else, it
                receives the file name of dhe directory which is currently
                scanned. The actual error is returned by IoErr() then.

                The Error Hook result informs oBuildDirInfoA() about how to
                go on. It *must* always be one of the values as defined in
                the oBDI_OnError Tag description:

                oBDION_Continue

                  - Continues scanning, gaining as much information as possible.

                oBDION_Break

                  - Breaks the scan at the current position and returns the
                    oDirInfo structure as-is.

                oBDION_Abort

                  - Completely aborts, freeing back all ressources.

                Error Hook example:

                ULONG __saveds __asm ErrorHookEntry (register __a0 struct Hook * hook,
                                                     register __a2 APTR          object,
                                                     register __a1 APTR          message);
                {
                  oMsgFault("File Error", "Error while scanning %s", object);

                  if (HardDisk_Is_Damaged_But_We_Must_Get_What_We_Can)
                  {
                    return(oBDI_Continue);
                  }
                  else if (Shit_But_Lets_See_What_We_Have)
                  {
                    return(oBDI_Break);
                  }
                  else /* if (All_Or_Nothing) */
                  {
                    return(oBDION_Abort);
                  }
                }

                If oBDI_Recursive isn't set, the ScanInfo Hook is only called once.

            oBDI_SortOrder

                ULONG. The DirTree created by oBuildDirInfoA() comes always
                alphabetically sorted. With this Tag, you may choose a primary
                sort order, which may be one of:

                oBDISO_DirsFirst   - Directories first

                oBDISO_FilesFirst  - Files first

                oBDISO_Mixed       - Strictly sorted, files & dirs mixed

                Ignored if oBDI_BuildDirTree isn't set. Default: oBDISO_Mixed.

            oBDI_NoDirs

                BOOL. If TRUE, directories get skipped (from adding to the
                oDirInfo->DirCount and, if used, from adding to the directory
                tree). Only files get added (with full path). Default: FALSE.

            oBDI_NoFiles

                BOOL. If TRUE, files get skipped (from adding to oDirInfo->FileCount
                & ByteCount and, if used, from adding to the directory tree).
                oBDI_NoDirs and oBDI_NoFiles exclude each other; if both are set
                to TRUE, oBuildDirInfoA() returns NULL. Default: FALSE.

            oBDI_OnError

                ULONG. There are several things which may happen when trying
                to scan a directory. oBuildDirInfoA() always fails when running
                out of memory, where all ressources get freed back immediately
                and IoError gets set to ERROR_NO_FREE_STORE.

                For other errors, the oBDI_OnError Tag allows to specify what to
                do in such cases. For example, this could be ERROR_OBJECT_IN_USE
                when trying to examine a write-locked sub-directory (recursively).
                Another error source may be a real filing system problem or a
                disk read error. However, this Tag provides three ways to react:

                oBDION_Continue

                  - Continues scanning, gaining as much information as possible.

                oBDION_Break

                  - Breaks the scan at the current position and returns the
                    oDirInfo structure as is.

                oBDION_Abort

                  - Completely aborts, freeing back all ressources.

                Default: oBDION_Abort.

                Note: the return code of an Error Hook, if used, overrides the
                oBDI_OnError Tag. This Tag is useful when not using an Error Hook.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        oDirInfo        - An oDirInfo structure, filled with all requested
                          information, or NULL on failure. Use IoErr() to
                          get information about the error. The oDirInfo structure
                          must be freed using @{"oFreeDirInfo()" link "oFreeDirInfo"}.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oFreeDirInfo() " link "oFreeDirInfo"}
@endnode
@node oCheckSum "OpenUtil.library / Misc. Functions / oCheckSum()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oCheckSum      -- Calculate a data CheckSum for a given Buffer (V2)

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oCheckSum (Type, Buffer, Size, LastCheckSum)
                    D0     A0     D1        A1

        ULONG oCheckSum (ULONG, void *, ULONG, ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function calculates a data checksum for the contents of a given
        memory block.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Type     - Type of CheckSum calculation to use. Currently, there are:

                   oCSTYPE_CRC_32AX366

                     32Bit-CRC type CheckSum, based on the polynomial
                     x^32+x^26+x^23+x^22+x^16+x^12+x^11+x^10+x^8+x^7+x^5+x^4+x^2+x^1+x^0.

                     ANSI X3.66 standard CRC, as used with the CCITT X.25
                     protocol. Should be your default choice, since 16-Bit
                     CRCs are not as safe as 32-Bit CRCs.

                     Usage: Size may be anything >0 including odd values.
                            Result is a ULONG value (as defined).

                   oCSTYPE_CRC_16a

                     Standard 16Bit-CRC type CheckSum, based on the polynomial
                     x^16+x^15+x^2+1.

                     Arc archives contain such CRCs.

                     Usage: Size may be anything >0 including odd values.
                            Result is an UWORD value.

                   oCSTYPE_CRC_CCITT

                     Another 16Bit-CRC (Cyclic Redundancy Check) type CheckSum,
                     based on the polynomial x^16+x^12+x^5+1.

                     This one is used by the XModem file transfer protocol; note
                     that this method isn't very safe. For those who need this.

                     Usage: Size may be anything >0 including odd values.
                            Result is an UWORD value.

        Buffer       - A Buffer holding the data to calculate the CheckSum of.

        Size         - Number of bytes to process. Must be >0 and is only
                       limited by the CheckSum calculation Type used.

        LastCheckSum - Used for block-wise checking huge amounts of data.
                       If you pass NULL here, a new CheckSum is calculated,
                       else if you pass the Result of the previous oCheckSum()
                       call, this will continue calculating the same CheckSum for
                       continuous blocks of the same file. The last oCheckSum()
                       call will then return the overall CheckSum. Refer to the
                       example below.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        CheckSum     - Even if defined as ULONG, the Result data size depends
                       on the CheckSum calculation Type used. If Result is
                       defined as being smaller than 32Bit, the unused upper
                       bits will be NULL.

                       Normally, this function can't fail but, however, if you've
                       passed invalid arguments, IoErr() will return an error
                       code.

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
        @{"  C  " link "CXoCheckSum"}

  @{b}NOTES@{ub}
        All CRC type CheckSums are calculated using pre-defined CRC tables
        for very fast calculation.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)
@endnode
@node CXoCheckSum "OpenUtil.library / Misc. Functions / oCheckSum(): C example"
/*
   Full example program which calculates a CheckSum for any file of any size.

   Shell usage: ThisProgram <FileName>
*/

#include <proto/exec.h>
#include <proto/dos.h>
#include <proto/OpenUtil.h>

#include <exec/memory.h>
#include <libraries/OpenUtil.h>

struct OpenUtilLibrary * OpenUtilBase;

long    MyCalcFileCRC(STRPTR FileName, UBYTE * Buffer, ULONG BufSize, ULONG * FileCRC);

#define BUFSIZE    (256*1024)

long main(void)
{
  STRPTR  FileName;
  ULONG   FileCRC = 0;
  UBYTE * MyBuffer;
  long    ReturnCode = RETURN_FAIL;

  if (OpenUtilBase = (struct OpenUtilLibrary *)OpenLibrary(OPENUTILNAME, OPENUTILVERSION))
  {
    FileName = GetArgStr();
    FileName[oStrLen(FileName)-1] = 0;  /* quick example hack */

    if (MyBuffer = oAllocVecPooled(0, BUFSIZE, MEMF_PUBLIC))
    {
      if (MyCalcFileCRC(FileName, MyBuffer, BUFSIZE, &FileCRC))
      {
        oMsgInfo("Result", "FileCRC = 0x%08lx", FileCRC);
        ReturnCode = RETURN_OK;
      }
      oFreeVecPooled(MyBuffer);
    }
    else
    {
      oMsgInfo("Error", "Out of memory.");
    }
    CloseLibrary((struct Library *)OpenUtilBase);
  }
  else
  {
    Printf("Can't open %s version %ld", OPENUTILNAME, OPENUTILVERSION);
  }
  return(ReturnCode);
}

// Next: MyCalcFileCRC(), which returns boolean-success.

long MyCalcFileCRC(STRPTR FileName, UBYTE * Buffer, ULONG BufSize, ULONG * FileCRC)
{
  BPTR    CRCFile;
  ULONG   ReadSize;
  ULONG   CRC;
  long    Error = 0;

  CRC = *FileCRC;

  if (CRCFile = Open(FileName, MODE_OLDFILE))
  {
    do
    {
      if ((ReadSize = Read(CRCFile, Buffer, BufSize)) != -1)
      {
        if (ReadSize)
        {
          CRC = oCheckSum(oCSTYPE_CRC_32AX366, Buffer, ReadSize, CRC);
        }
      }
      else
      {
        oMsgFault("Error", "Error while reading %s", FileName);
        Error = IoErr();
      }
    }while(ReadSize == BufSize);

    Close(CRCFile);
  }
  else
  {
    oMsgFault("Error", "Can't open %s", FileName);
    Error = IoErr();
  }
  SetIoErr(Error);
  if (Error)
  {
    return(FALSE);
  }
  *FileCRC = CRC;
  return(TRUE);
}
@endnode
@node oChrCut "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oChrCut()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oChrCut -- cut a string at search char position

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oChrCut (String, CutChar, MaxRange)
                   A0       D0       D1

        STRPTR oChrCut (STRPTR, UBYTE, ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        Cut a string at the first position of a specified char.
        The CutChar is searched inside the source string; if a match is
        found, the right part of the source string gets cut at that position.
        If nothing was found, nothing gets changed. This function is not
        case-sensitive.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        String          - The string to truncate

        CutChar         - The char to search for

        MaxRange        - the maximum string length to search for the Char,
                          which normally is sizeof(String).

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Result points to the (new) end position of the passed string, no
        matter if the CutChar was found or not. Result always points to
        the trailing NULL byte of the string.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oChrCutCase() " link "oChrCutCase"}, @{" oStrCut() " link "oStrCut"}
@endnode
@node oChrCutCase "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oChrCutCase()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oChrCutCase -- cut a string at a search char position

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oChrCutCase (String, CutChar, MaxRange)
                       A0      D0        D1

        STRPTR oChrCutCase (STRPTR, UBYTE, ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        Cut a string at the first position of a specified char.
        The CutChar is searched inside the source string; if a match is
        found, the right part of the source string gets cut at that position.
        If nothing was found, nothing gets changed. This function is case-
        sensitive.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        String          - The string to truncate

        CutChar         - The char to search for

        MaxRange        - the maximum string length to search for the Char,
                          which normally is sizeof(String).

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Result points to the (new) end position of the passed string, no
        matter if the CutChar was found or not. Result always points to
        the trailing NULL byte of the string.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oChrCut() " link "oChrCut"}, @{" oStrCut() " link "oStrCut"}
@endnode
@node oClearList "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oClearList()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oClearList      -- delete all records in an Exec List

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oClearList (Base)
                     A0

        struct List * oClearList (struct List *)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function empties an exec List and frees all records by calling
        @{"oFreeVecPooled()" link "oFreeVecPooled"}. So all List Nodes (records) must have been allocated
        using @{"oAllocVecPooledA()" link "oAllocVecPooledA"} or any other OpenUtil function.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Base            - Exec List (may be empty).

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        The passed List (emptied).

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oDeleteList() " link "oDeleteList"}, @{" oCutList() " link "oCutList"}, @{" oRemExecHeader() " link "oRemExecHeader"}
@endnode
@node oClearMem "OpenUtil.library / Memory Functions / oClearMem()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oClearMem   -- Clear a memory block

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oClearMem (Buffer, Size)
                    A0      D0

        APTR oClearMem (APTR, ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function clears a memory block by filling it with null-bytes.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Buffer     - The Buffer to clear.

        Size       - Number of bytes; may be odd.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Buffer     - The Buffer you've passed.

  @{b}NOTES@{ub}
        This function uses @{"oFillMem()" link "oFillMem"} for clearing a buffer, which is optimized
        for larger buffers.

  @{b}BUGS@{ub}
        Due to function internal reasons, Size is currently limited to 13.631.280
        bytes, so if you're working with a Buffer larger than approx. 12MB, you'll
        need to call this function twice or several times.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oFillMem() " link "oFillMem"}
@endnode
@node oCloseMsgWait "OpenUtil.library / User Interface / oCloseMsgWait()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oCloseMsgWait   -- Remove an oMsgWait Window opened using @{"oOpenMsgWaitA()" link "oOpenMsgWaitA"}

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oCloseMsgWait (MsgWait)
                          A0

        void oCloseMsgWait (struct oMsgWait *)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        Closes and frees an oMsgWait Window & all related ressources.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        MsgWait     - An oMsgWait structure as created by @{"oOpenMsgWaitA()" link "oOpenMsgWaitA"}.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oOpenMsgWaitA() " link "oOpenMsgWaitA"}, @{" oUpdateMsgWait() " link "oUpdateMsgWait"}, 
        @{" oCreateStatusBarA() " link "oCreateStatusBarA"}
@endnode
@node oCompareMem "OpenUtil.library / Memory Functions / oCompareMem()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oCompareMem     -- Compare memory (V2)

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oCompareMem (Source, Destination, Size)
                       A0        A1        D0

        void * oCompareMem (void *, void *, ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function compares the first <Size> bytes of two passed memory blocks.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Source        - A pointer to somewhere in memory.

        Destination   - Another pointer to somewhere in memory.

        Size          - Number of bytes to compare.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        SourceAt      - NULL if Source contains the same as Destination, else
                        Result points to the first Source byte which doesn't
                        match with the corresponding byte in Destination.

  @{b}NOTES@{ub}
        If Size is dividable by 4 and both pointers are even, oCompareMem()
        automatically compares long-vs-long instead of byte-vs-byte.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)
@endnode
@node oCountList "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oCountList()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oCountList      -- Return the number of Nodes linked to an Exec List

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oCountList (Base)
                     A0

        ULONG oCountList (struct List *)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function returns the number of Nodes linked to a given Exec List.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Base            - Exec List (may be empty).

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Amount  - Number of records or NULL (List is empty).

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oListIsEmpty() " link "oListIsEmpty"}
@endnode
@node oCreateITextChainA "OpenUtil.library / User Interface / oCreateITextChainA()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oCreateITextChainA -- Convert ASCII text incl. line feeds to IText chain

        oCreateITextChain  -- varargs stub for oCreateITextChainA()

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oCreateITextChainA (Text, Font, Format, Spacing, Argv)
                             A0    A1     D0       D1     A2

        oCreateITextChain  (Text, Font, Format, Spacing, ...)

        struct IntuiText * oCreateITextChainA (STRPTR, struct TextAttr *, long, ULONG, long *)

        struct IntuiText * oCreateITextChain  (STRPTR, struct TextAttr *, long, ULONG, ...)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function converts a string to an IText chain which may be directly
        printed using PrintIText().

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Text            - A text string which may include LineFeed characters
                          and RawDoFmt() commands. The last char of this string
                          gets skipped if it's a LineFeed (0x10) character to
                          avoid an empty text line added at the bottom.)

        Font            - (struct TextAttr). The font to use for the IntuiText.

        Format          - OU_LEFT, OU_RIGHT or OU_CENTERED will format the
                          text lines as it says. NULL is equal to OU_LEFT.

        Spacing         - Text line spacing in pixels (NULL = no spacing)

        Argv            - RawDoFmt() args for the passed Text

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        IText           - A fully initialized IText chain, ready for printing
                          or NULL if out of memory. Use @{"oDeleteITextChain()" link "oDeleteITextChain"} to
                          free it back to memory. If not out of memory, the
                          IText chain will always be valid, even if the passed
                          string is empty.

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}

        C:

        struct IntuiText * IText;

        struct Window    * TextWindow;

        STRPTR String    = "Congratulations to %s,\n"
                           "who hast just won\n"
                           "%ld millions.";

        if (IText = oCreateITextChain(String,
                                      OpenUtilBase->OU_Topaz8,
                                      OU_CENTER,
                                      2,
                                      "Fred Flintstone",50))
        {
          if (TextWindow = OpenWindowTags(0,
                                          WA_Left,         200,
                                          WA_Top,          100,
                                          WA_GimmeZeroZero,TRUE,
                                          WA_InnerWidth,   oITextWidth (IText),
                                          WA_InnerHeight,  oITextHeight(IText),
                                          WA_DragBar,      FALSE,
                                          TAG_DONE))
          {
            PrintIText(TextWindow->RPort,IText,0,0);

            Delay(200); /* wait a while to watch.. */

            CloseWindow(TextWindow);
          }
          oDeleteITextChain(IText);
        }

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oDeleteITextChain() " link "oDeleteITextChain"}, @{" oITextHeight() " link "oITextHeight"}, @{" oITextWidth() " link "oITextWidth"}
@endnode
@node oCreateList "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oCreateList()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oCreateList      -- Allocate & initialize an Exec List

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oCreateList (MemPool)
                       A0

        struct List * oCreateList (void *)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function allocates and initializes an Exec List.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        MemPool         - An Exec Memory Pool where to allocate the List Header
                          from. If NULL, the main system memory is used.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Base            - An initialized Exec List or NULL (out of memory).
                          This List header must be freed using @{"oFreeVecPooled()" link "oFreeVecPooled"}
                          or any other Openutil function.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oDeleteList() " link "oDeleteList"}, @{" oRemExecHeader() " link "oRemExecHeader"}
@endnode
@node oCreatePath "OpenUtil.library / File Operations / oCreatePath()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oCreatePath -- Create a directory including all sub directories (V2)

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oCreatePath (Name, Flags)
                      A0    D0

        long oCreatePath (STRPTR, ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        If you have a string describing a path with various sub paths which
        are not existsing or only in parts you can use oCreatePath() to let all
        these paths be created in one go.
        
        You need to use oCDF_CREATESUBDIRS as a Flag to enable this feature.
        Without oCDF_CREATESUBDIRS oCreatePath() works like CreateDir() from
        dos.library and creates only a single directory.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Name         - The string describing a chain of directories to be created.

        Flags        - oCDF_CREATESUBDIRS to enable the creation of all non-
                       existing sub directories.

                       oCPFF_OVERRIDEEXISTS to continue also if the directory
                       to be created already exists. In this case oCreatePath()
                       locks the already existing directory exclusively.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        DirLock      - NULL if something fails, else a lock to the last created
                       directory (the requested one).

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        David 'Strider/tRSi' Wettig (strider@trsi.de)
@endnode
@node oCreateRndSeed "OpenUtil.library / Misc. Functions / oCreateRndSeed()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oCreateRndSeed -- Alloc & init an oRndSeed structure for use with @{"oRandom()" link "oRandom"}

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oCreateRndSeed (RenewRate)
                            D0

        struct oRndSeed * oCreateRndSeed (ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function allocates & initializes an oRndSeed structure which is
        required for @{"oRandom()" link "oRandom"} calls. It holds information about how to draw
        the next random number.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        RenewRate  - Every time after <RenewRate> calls to @{"oRandom()" link "oRandom"}, the current
                     System E-Clock micro seconds value gets added to the Random
                     Seed before calculating a new random number. This influences
                     the Results by custom time periods, like user input delays.
                     Such random numbers can no longer be foreseen. Beyond that,
                     drawing values which fulfil all needed characteristics of
                     real random numbers is a common problem for pure math-based
                     pseudo-random generators. However, by passing NULL here,
                     E-Clock adding is disabled.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        oRndSeed   - An oRndSeed structure or NULL (out of memory).

                     oRndSeed->RndSeed gets initialized with a start value
                     which depends on the current System E-Clock value.
                     If you need identical rows of pseudo random numbers,
                     call CreateRndSeed(0). Then, set oRndSeed->RndSeed to a
                     constant value before starting a series of @{"oRandom()" link "oRandom"} calls.

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
        The @{"oRandom()" link "oRandom"} description includes a usage example.

  @{b}NOTES@{ub}
        It seems that the used random generator fits most requirements, but
        who knows ? If you need real random numbers, use a small (non-zero)
        RenewRate value.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oDeleteRndSeed() " link "oDeleteRndSeed"}, @{" oRandom() " link "oRandom"}
@endnode
@node oCreateStatusBarA "OpenUtil.library / User Interface / oCreateStatusBarA()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oCreateStatusBarA   -- Create a status bar used for progress indication.
        oCreateStatusBar    -- varargs stub for oCreateStatusBarA()

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oCreateStatusBarA (Window, Left, Top, Width, Height, Tags)
                             A0     D0    D1    D2     D3     A1

        oCreateStatusBar  (Window, Left, Top, Width, Height, FirstTag, ...)

        struct oStatusBar * oCreateStatusBarA (struct Window *, long, long, long, long, struct TagItem *)

        struct oStatusBar * oCreateStatusBar  (struct Window *, long, long, long, long, Tag, ...)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function creates a Status Bar object and initializes a RastPort
        region for drawing a progress display bar.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Window          - A Window where to draw the Status Bar.

        Left            - The x-position of the upper-left corner of the Status
                          Bar in the Window's RastPort.

        Top             - The y-position of the upper-left corner of the Status
                          Bar in the Window's RastPort.

        Width           - Overall width of the Status Bar.

        Height          - Overall height of the Status Bar.

        Tags            - optional (else pass NULL):

                          oSTB_MAXVALUE

                          (ULONG). The maximum Value where the Status Bar gets
                          fully drawn, which equals 100% completed. For example,
                          if you're going to do some file action on 156 files,
                          you may prefer setting oSTB_MAXVALUE to 156 instead of
                          the default value of 100 (which draws the Status Bar
                          according to percentage values).

                          Note that very small values (example: 5) will cause
                          the Status Bar to grow block-wise instead of scrolling
                          smoothly up to full size.

                          oSTB_DRAWBORDER

                          BOOL. If TRUE, oCreateStatusBarA() draws a border around
                          the Status Bar. The inner Size of the Bar gets reduced
                          by the border thickness.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        oStatusBar      - An oStatusBar structure or NULL (out of memory or no
                          VisualInfo available).

                          The rectangle area for the Status Bar gets erased.
                          If oSTB_DRAWBORDER is set, a Border is drawn around the
                          Status Bar.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oDeleteStatusBar() " link "oDeleteStatusBar"}, @{" oUpdateStatusBar() " link "oUpdateStatusBar"},
        @{" oOpenMsgWaitA() " link "oOpenMsgWaitA"}
@endnode
@node oCutList "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oCutList()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oCutList      -- Truncate an Exec List from a given start Node position

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oCutList (Base, StartRecord, Flags)
                   A0        A1        D0

        long oCutList (struct List *, struct Node *, ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function removes and frees all Nodes in a List, beginning at the
        given StartRecord.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Base            - An Exec List which contains Nodes which must have been
                          allocated using @{"oAllocVecPooledA()" link "oAllocVecPooledA"} or any other
                          OpenUtil function.

        StartRecord     - A Node which @{b}must@{ub} be linked to the passed List.

        Flags           - oCLSF_UP

                          Truncates the list in upward direction.

                          oCLSF_EXCLUSIVE

                          Excludes the passed Node from being deleted.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        NumDeleted      - Number of records (Nodes) deleted from the List.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oClearList() " link "oClearList"}, @{" oDeleteList() " link "oDeleteList"}, @{" oRemExecHeader() " link "oRemExecHeader"}
@endnode
