  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        David 'Strider/tRSi' Wettig (strider@trsi.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oExists() " link "oExists"}, @{" oFileSize() " link "oFileSize"}, @{" oGetProtection() " link "oGetProtection"}
@endnode
@node oDivU64L "OpenUtil.library / Math Functions / oDivU64L()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oDivU64L -- perform a full 64-bit division

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oDivU64L (SrcHi, SrcLo, DestHi, DestLo)
                    D0     D1     A0      A1

        long oDivU64L (ULONG, ULONG, ULONG *, ULONG *)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function divides one 64-Bit number by another.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        SrcHi   - The upper 32 bits of the source value (which to divide by Dest)

        SrcLo   - The lower 32 bits of the source value

        DestHi  - A pointer to a ULONG which holds the upper 32 bits of
                  the divisor value and which will receive the upper 32 bits
                  of the division result.

        DestLo  - A pointer to a ULONG which holds the lower 32 bits of
                  the divisor value and which will receive the lower 32 bits
                  of the division result.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Success   BOOL. If TRUE, DestHi and DestLo contain the division result;
                  FALSE indicates a division by zero error.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oMulU64L() " link "oMulU64L"}, @{" oAddU64() " link "oAddU64"}, @{" oSubU64() " link "oSubU64"}
@endnode
@node oExists "OpenUtil.library / File Operations / oExists()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oExists -- Check if a file (or drawer) already exists (V2)

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oExists (FileName)
                    A0

        long oExists (STRPTR)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function checks for the existance of a file or directory.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Name         - Full AmigaDOS file name.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Exists       - BOOL. If TRUE, the file (or dir) already exists, no matter
                       if it's currently in use.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{"oFileSize()" link "oFileSize"}, @{"oGetProtection()" link "oGetProtection"}
@endnode
@node oFCopyMove "OpenUtil.library / File Operations / oFCopyMove"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oFCopyMove       -- Copy or move a file or directory

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oFCopyMove (Source, Destination, Buffer, BufSize, Flags)
                      A0        A1         A2       D0      D1

        long oFCopyMove (STRPTR, STRPTR, APTR, ULONG, ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function copies or moves a single file or directory to another
        location.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Source          - Source file (or directory) name. If Source is a
                          directory, it only gets copied/moved if it's empty.

        Destination     - Destination name. If Destination is an already existing
                          directory, Source gets put into that directory using
                          the same file name as passed, so this function behaves
                          like a Shell copy/move command. Refer to the examples
                          below.

        Buffer          - When copying lots of files, you may pass a Buffer here
                          to avoid allocating & freeing a Buffer with each call;
                          if you pass NULL here, oFCopyMove() allocates one.

        BufSize         - Passing NULL here sets BufSize to the current default
                          size, which is normally 256K. If you've passed a Buffer,
                          you must pass your BufSize here, since the default
                          BufSize is a changeable value. If you don't use an own
                          Buffer, this argument sets the allocation size.

                          Note: oFCopyMove() automatically reduces the Buffer
                          allocation size if it's bigger than the Source file.

        Flags           - oFCMF_MOVE

                          If this flag is set, the file/dir gets moved to the
                          new location, else oFCopyMove() creates a copy.

                        - oFCMF_KEEPINFO

                          If this flag is set, Destination will get the same
                          file comment and protection bits as the Source file
                          except the Archive bit, which always gets cleared ("not
                          archived"). If this flag isn't set, the file gets the
                          default bit mask (----RWED).

                        - oFCMF_REPLACE

                          If Destination already exists, it only gets overwritten
                          if this flag is set.

                        - oFCMF_FORCE

                          This flag is used to override the Source and (if exists)
                          the Destination protection bits (READ / DELETE).

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Success         BOOL. If FALSE, call IoErr() to get an error code.

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
        C:
                // Copy OpenUtil.library to LIBS:

                oFCopyMove ("OpenUtil/libs/OpenUtil.library", "LIBS:", 0, 0, 0);

                // or (exactly the same effect):

                oFCopyMove ("OpenUtil/libs/OpenUtil.library", "LIBS:OpenUtil.library", 0, 0, 0);

                // Another example:

                oFCopyMove ("DH0:Test", "DH1:Test", 0, 0, 0);

                // For the last call above i'll try an exact description for
                // those who need clarity there. The following situations are
                // possible; note that if oFCMF_REPLACE isn't set, nothing gets
                // overwritten anyway, else:
                //
                // 1. Destination is a file.
                //    Action: Dest. gets overwritten with the Source file/dir.
                //
                // 2. Destination is a Directory
                //    Action: Src gets copied/moved @{b}into@{ub} the Dest. directory.
                //    If the Dest. directory contains a file of the same name,
                //    the file gets overwritten with Source. In the last Example,
                //    Dest is "DH1:Test/Test" then. If "DH1:Test/Test" exists
                //    and is also a directory, oFCopyMove() aborts and IoErr()
                //    will then report ERROR_OBJECT_EXISTS, even if oFCMF_REPLACE
                //    is set.
                //
                // Rules:
                //
                // 1. oFCopyMove() never overwrites directores.
                //
                // 2. oFCopyMove() aborts if Source is a non-empty directory.
                //

  @{b}NOTES@{ub}
        Provide at least 1500 bytes of Stack space for this function.

        oFCopyMove() is a medium-level function which calls @{"oFHCopy()" link "oFHCopy"} whenever
        renaming isn't possible. The next higher function is @{"oFileDirHandleA()" link "oFileDirHandleA"},
        which can do much more than just copying/moving a single file.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{"oFHCopy()" link "oFHCopy"}, @{"oFileDirHandleA()" link "oFileDirHandleA"}
@endnode
@node oFHCopy "OpenUtil.library / File Operations / oFHCopy()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oFHCopy          -- copy a file (or a part of) to another

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oFHCopy (Source, Destination, Size, Buffer, BufSize)
                   A0         A1       D0     A2       D1

        long oFHCopy (BPTR, BPTR, ULONG, APTR, ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function is usually used whenever OpenUtil.library copies one file
        to another. It awaits two File Handles instead of file names and needs
        some extra paramaters you probably won't like to deal with.

        For copying files by name, refer to @{"oFCopyMove()" link "oFCopyMove"}.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Source          - Source File Handle, already seeked to the needed read
                          start position.

        Destination     - Destination File Handle, already seeked to the needed
                          write start position.

        Size            - Number of bytes to copy. If this value is greater
                          than the remaining Source file size, the file gets
                          copied until EOF (end of file).

        Buffer          - When copying lots of files, you may pass a Buffer here
                          to avoid allocating & freeing a Buffer with each call;
                          if you pass NULL here, oFHCopy() allocates one.

        BufSize         - Passing NULL here sets BufSize to the current default
                          size, which is normally 256K. If you've passed a Buffer,
                          you must pass your BufSize here, since the default
                          BufSize is a changeable value. If you don't use an own
                          Buffer, this argument sets the allocation size.

                          Note: oFHCopy reduces the Buffer allocation size if
                          it's greater than the passed copy Size or the remaining
                          Source file size.
  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        BytesCopied     - long. -1 indicates an error. IoErr() will then return
                          an AmigaDOS Error Code. If successful, Result equals
                          the number of bytes copied. Result can be smaller
                          than the requested Size because oFHCopy() doesn't
                          fail if the remaining Source file size is smaller
                          than the requested copy Size.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{"oFCopyMove()" link "oFCopyMove"}, @{"oFileDirHandleA()" link "oFileDirHandleA"}
@endnode
@node oFileDirHandleA "OpenUtil.library / File Operations / oFileDirHandleA()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oFileDirHandleA -- perform misc DOS operations cursive/recursive (V2).
        oFileDirHandle  -- varargs stub for oFileDirHandleA().

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oFileDirHandleA (Source, Destination, Tags)
                           A0         A1       A2

        oFileDirHandle  (Source, Destination, FirstTag, ...)

        long oFileDirHandleA (STRPTR, STRPTR, struct TagItem *)

        long oFileDirHandle  (STRPTR, STRPTR, Tag, ...)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        oFileDirHandleA() can be used to perform different cursive/recursive DOS
        operations such as counting bytes, sizes and number of dirs (recursive),
        deleting files, moving files, copying files, setting file comments or
        modifying file protection bits.

        oFileDirHandleA() supports a hook for various things like to inform
        an application about every single file or directory step it is to
        work with as the next task, because of this such a hook can work like a
        filter to skip single files or complete directory trees or whatever.
        The hook can also be used to create your own progress indicator.
        The hook will also be called as a kind of an error-hook.
        Everytime an error happens (except of very root errors on calling
        oFileDirHandleA() the first time) the hook will be called so that
        an application can decide on checking the error code what to do.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Source       - Standard AmigaDOS file/dir name.

        Destination  - The Destination file/directory. May be NULL if there
                       is no Destination needed for the specified Action.

        Tags         - Currently, the following Tags are defined:

                       oFDH_Action - Default: oFDH_ACTION_COUNT

                         This Tag is used to specify the action to perform,
                         which can be one of:

                         oFDH_ACTION_COUNT

                           Only perform a file/byte/dir count.
                           Destination not needed then.

                         oFDH_ACTION_DELETE

                           Deletes files/dirs/files and dirs.
                           Destination not needed.

                         oFDH_ACTION_MOVE to move files/dirs.

                         oFDH_ACTION_COPY to copy files/dirs.

                         oFDH_ACTION_COMMENT to comment files/dirs.

                         oFDH_ACTION_SETPROTECTION set protection bits on
                         files/dirs.

                         oFDH_ACTION_CLEARPROTECTION to clear protection bits
                         of files/dirs.

                         oFDH_ACTION_SWAPPROTECTION  to swap protection bits
                         of files/dirs.

                       oFDH_Recursive - Default: FALSE
                       Indicate a recursive scan.

                       oFDH_Protection - Default: NONE / Conditional MUST
                       A protection bit mask which MUST be used if oFDH_Action
                       is oFDH_ACTION_SETPROTECTION, oFDH_ACTION_CLEARPROTECTION
                       or oFDH_ACTION_SWAPPROTECTION else oFileDirHandleA()
                       returns oFDH_RESULT_NOPROTBITMASK.

                       oFDH_DirProtection - Default: FALSE
                       Indicate if you want to set the protection bits on
                       directories too.

                       oFDH_MaxCopyBuffer - Default: 1048576 bytes
                       The max copy buffer if oFDH_Action is oFDH_ACTION_MOVE
                       or oFDH_ACTION_COPY.

                       oFDH_ForceDelete - Default: FALSE
                       Delete also files and dirs which do have the delete
                       protection bit set.

                       oFDH_DirComments - Default: FALSE
                       Indicate that you want to set comments also on directories
                       if oFDH_Action is oFDH_ACTION_COMMENT.

                       oFDH_FileCount - Default: NULL (not used)
                       An ULONG pointer (ULONG *) which will receive the number 
                       of files.
                       It's important that you initialize your ULONG *
                       contents (to 0 for example), because oFileDirHandleA()
                       does not do this for you, because of cases where
                       more calls of oFileDirHandleA() are needed with
                       counting through all of them.

                       oFDH_ByteCount - Default: NULL (not used)
                       An ULONG pointer (ULONG *) which will receive the number
                       of bytes.
                       It's important that you initialize your ULONG *
                       contents (to 0 for example), because oFileDirHandleA()
                       does not do this for you, because of cases where
                       more calls of oFileDirHandleA() are needed with
                       counting through all of them.

                       oFDH_DirCount - Default: NULL (not used)
                       An ULONG pointer (ULONG *) which will receive the number 
                       of sub directories.
                       It's important that you initialize your ULONG *
                       contents (to 0 for example), because oFileDirHandleA()
                       does not do this for you, because of cases where
                       more calls of oFileDirHandleA() are needed with
                       counting through all of them.

                       oFDH_MemoryPool - Default: NULL (not used)
                       A pointer to a memory pool created by using CreatePool() / 
                       exec.library which will be used for every allocation 
                       oFileDirHandleA() does - and there can be lots of them in 
                       recursive mode. If oFDH_MemoryPool isn't used the 
                       allocation goes from the system main memory instead.

                       oFDH_StatusHook - Default: NONE (not used)
                       The 'struct Hook' pointer to support an application Hook
                       for use as described below. If NULL or not set no hook
                       will be called.

                       oFDH_StatusHookUserData - Default: NONE (not used)
                       To add your own datas to the struct oFDHHookData -> UserData
                       field your hook will receive in A2 ("object").
                       By the way - it's also possible to use h_Data of struct
                       Hook to pass own data to the Hook.
                       If NULL or not set A2 ("object") receives NULL.
                       oFDH_StatusHookUserData will only be used if oFDH_StatusHook
                       is used too.

                       oFDH_oFCopyMoveFlags - Default: oFCMF_KEEPINFO
                       The typical flags for @{"oFCopyMove()" link "oFCopyMove"} which will be used for
                       copying/moving files. Needed if you want some special flags
                       to be supported. oFileDirHandleA() only changes 'oFCMF_MOVE'.

                       oFDH_OnError - Default: oFDH_HOOK_RETURN_ABORT
                       Default setting dedicated for the case where no hook is used
                       to react on errors. You can use oFDH_HOOK_RETURN_OK,
                       oFDH_HOOK_RETURN_SKIP or oFDH_HOOK_RETURN_ABORT here.

                       oFDH_Pattern - Default: NULL (not used)
                       Used to specify a pattern string for all files found in the
                       passed Source directory.

                       oFDH_CreateSubDirs - Default: FALSE
                       Needed if you call oFileDirHandleA() with a Destination 
                       string which describes a path containing sub dirs which 
                       don't already exist, so oFileDirHandleA() also creates
                       them if ti_Data is set to TRUE. @{"oMakePath()" link oMakePath"}
                       is called to do this.

  @{b}HOOKS@{ub}
        The StatusHook can receive positive or negative errors. Negative errors
        signal a fatal failure, like out of memory. No matter which ReturnCode
        is set by the callback Hook, oFileDirHandleA() will then abort with an
        error right after calling the Hook. On positive errors, the callback
        Hook can decide (by ReturnCode) if oFileDirHandleA() shall continue,
        skip the current entry or abort the operation.

        To make all those things possible and to prevent your application
        of using __saveds or whatever unnice things your hook receives
        in register A2 a structure called 'oFDHHookData', which contains,
        for example, OpenUtilBase - which also contains most needed Library
        Bases for use by the Hook.

        If multiple files are processed, 'oFDHHookData' also contains a valid
        FileInfoBlock of the file which to process next. In the case of an
        error, This field may be NULL, for example, if Examine() failed.

        'oFDHHookData' also contains the TagList you can read if your
        Hook needs to find out what tags have been set on calling
        oFileDirHandleA() from your main code to be more flexible
        and universial with your hook, but *NERVER* change something
        in the TagList! It's strictly read only and can be used i.e.
        to read the current oFDH_FileCount, oFDH_ByteCount and
        oFDH_DirCount values to update some kind of indicator.

        'oFDHHookData' contains also the current Lock, the source
        and destination pointers, both internal buffers which contain
        the new created sub directories and the pattern buffer.

        All these pointers are not valid in every case - so check them.
        
        'oFDHHookData' contains - very important - a variable called
        'StatusCode', which holds a value defined by oFDH_HOOKSTAT_<XXX>
        defines you will find in 'Include:libraries/OpenUtil.h'.
        They are describing why your hook is getting called.
        As told above there is a negative and positive possibility.
        oFDH_HOOKSTAT_UPDATE is being used in the most cases of a hook
        call and simply informs your hook about the next step, that's
        why oFDH_HOOKSTAT_UPDATE is the only exception which is not
        positive or negative - it's NULL.

        The last important thing to know about the Hook code is that
        there are some defined return codes your hook must use when
        returning to the library, which can be one of:

        oFDH_HOOK_RETURN_OK     - normally continues the operation.
        oFDH_HOOK_RETURN_SKIP   - skip the next step (file/entry)
        oFDH_HOOK_RETURN_ABORT  - terminate the oFileDirHandleA() call.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Error        - NULL if everything went well (== oFDH_RESULT_SUCCESS),
                       else one of the following error codes:

                       oFDH_RESULT_BUFFERALLOCFAIL if oFileDirHandleA() wasn't
                       able to allocate it's buffers.

                       oFDH_RESULT_DIRLOCKFAIL if oFileDirHandleA() wasn't able
                       to lock the source directory.

                       oFDH_RESULT_EXAMINEFAIL if oFileDirHandleA() wans't able
                       to examine the source directory.

                       oFDH_RESULT_DESTNOTDIR if Destination is no directory
                       in cases where it should be a directory.

                       oFDH_RESULT_SOURCENOTVALID if the Source pointer is not
                       valid (NULL or empty).

                       oFDH_RESULT_DESTNOTVALID if the Destination pointer is
                       not valid (NULL or empty on moving or copying.

                       oFDH_RESULT_NOPROTBITMASK if the oFDH_Protection
                       tag has not been set on doing a protection bit Action.

                       oFDH_RESULT_USERABORTREQUEST if the application hook
                       returns oFDH_HOOK_RETURN_ABORT.

                       oFDH_RESULT_REQUIREDTAGMISSING if no tags are set on calling
                       oFileDirHandleA().

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
        @{"  C  " link "CXoFileDirHandleA"}

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        David 'Strider/tRSi' Wettig (strider@trsi.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oFCopyMove() " link "oFCopyMove"}
        @{" oFHCopy() " link "oFHCopy"}
        @{" oMakePath() " link "oMakePath"}
        @{" oCreatePath() " link "oCreatePath"}
@endnode
@node CXoFileDirHandleA "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oFileDirHandleA(): C Example"

/* oFileDirHandleA() usage examples */

  ULONG FileCount = 0UL, // Must be initialized by us!
        ByteCount = 0UL, // Must be initialized by us!
        DirCount  = 0UL; // Must be initialized by us!

  //oFDH_ACTION_COUNT:

  Result = oFileDirHandle( "Sys:Tools/",
                           "",
                           oFDH_Action,        oFDH_ACTION_COUNT,
                           oFDH_FileCount,     (ULONG)&FileCount,
                           oFDH_ByteCount,     (ULONG)&ByteCount,
                           oFDH_DirCount,      (ULONG)&DirCount,
                           oFDH_Recursive,     TRUE,
                           TAG_DONE );
  //oFDH_ACTION_DELETE:

  Result = oFileDirHandle( "T:",
                           "",
                           oFDH_Action,        oFDH_ACTION_DELETE,
                           oFDH_FileCount,     (ULONG)&FileCount,
                           oFDH_ByteCount,     (ULONG)&ByteCount,
                           oFDH_DirCount,      (ULONG)&DirCount,
                           oFDH_Recursive,     TRUE,
                           TAG_DONE );

  //oFDH_ACTION_MOVE:

  Result = oFileDirHandle( "Sys:T",                // Slash or no slash makes no difference
                           "Sys:Temp/",
                           oFDH_Action,        oFDH_ACTION_MOVE,
                           oFDH_FileCount,     (ULONG)&FileCount,
                           oFDH_ByteCount,     (ULONG)&ByteCount,
                           oFDH_DirCount,      (ULONG)&DirCount,
                           oFDH_Recursive,     TRUE,
                           TAG_DONE );

  //oFDH_ACTION_COPY:

  Result = oFileDirHandle( "ENVARC:",
                           "ENV:",
                           oFDH_Action,        oFDH_ACTION_COPY,
                           oFDH_FileCount,     (ULONG)&FileCount,
                           oFDH_ByteCount,     (ULONG)&ByteCount,
                           oFDH_DirCount,      (ULONG)&DirCount,
                           oFDH_Recursive,     TRUE,
                           TAG_DONE );
  //oFDH_ACTION_COMMENT:

  Result = oFileDirHandle( "ENVARC:",
                           "Application config files.",
                           oFDH_Action,        oFDH_ACTION_COMMENT,
                           oFDH_FileCount,     (ULONG)&FileCount,
                           oFDH_ByteCount,     (ULONG)&ByteCount,
                           oFDH_DirCount,      (ULONG)&DirCount,
                           oFDH_Recursive,     TRUE,
                           oFDH_DirComments,   TRUE,
                           TAG_DONE );

  //oFDH_ACTION_SETPROTECTION:

  Result = oFileDirHandle( "S:Startup-Sequence",
                           "",
                           oFDH_Action,        oFDH_ACTION_SETPROTECTION,
                           oFDH_FileCount,     (ULONG)&FileCount,
                           oFDH_ByteCount,     (ULONG)&ByteCount,
                           oFDH_DirCount,      (ULONG)&DirCount,
                           oFDH_Protection,    FIBF_SCRIPT,
                           TAG_DONE );

  //oFDH_ACTION_CLEARPROTECTION:

  Result = oFileDirHandle( "RAM:",
                           "",
                           oFDH_Action,        oFDH_ACTION_CLEARPROTECTION,
                           oFDH_FileCount,     (ULONG)&FileCount,
                           oFDH_ByteCount,     (ULONG)&ByteCount,
                           oFDH_DirCount,      (ULONG)&DirCount,
                           oFDH_Protection,    FIBF_DELETE,
                           oFDH_DirProtection, TRUE,
                           oFDH_Recursive,     TRUE,
                           TAG_DONE );

  //oFDH_ACTION_SWAPPROTECTION:

  Result = oFileDirHandle( "Sys:Disk.info",
                           "",
                           oFDH_Action,        oFDH_ACTION_SWAPPROTECTION,
                           oFDH_FileCount,     (ULONG)&FileCount,
                           oFDH_ByteCount,     (ULONG)&ByteCount,
                           oFDH_DirCount,      (ULONG)&DirCount,
                           oFDH_Protection,    FIBF_ARCHIVE,
                           TAG_DONE );

  // To support a hook you need to do also the following:

  STATIC __asm ULONG AppHookFunc( register __a0 struct Hook         *Hook,
                                  register __a2 struct oFDHHookData *oFDHHookData,
                                  register __a1 APTR parms )
  {
    /*
     * Example hook.
     */

    struct IntuitionBase *IntuitionBase = oFDHHookData -> OpenUtilBase -> OU_IntuitionBase;
    struct EasyStruct    MyEasyStruct;

    // struct MyData *MyData = oFDHHookData -> UserData;

    switch( oFDHHookData -> StatusCode )
    {
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_EXAMINEFAIL:
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_DIRLOCKFAIL:
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_OUTOFMEMORY:
        return( oFDH_HOOK_RETURN_ABORT );
      break;
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_UPDATE:
        MyEasyStruct . es_StructSize   = sizeof( struct EasyStruct );
        MyEasyStruct . es_Flags        = 0;
        MyEasyStruct . es_Title        = "Example Hook";
        MyEasyStruct . es_GadgetFormat = "Ok!";
        if( oFDHHookData -> CurrentFIB )
        {
          MyEasyStruct . es_TextFormat = oFDHHookData -> CurrentFIB -> fib_FileName;
        }
        else
        {
          MyEasyStruct . es_TextFormat = "What a nice day!";
        }
        EasyRequestArgs( NULL, &MyEasyStruct, NULL, NULL );
      break;
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_BYTECOUNTFAIL:
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_GETPROTECTFAIL:
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_SETPROTECTFAIL:
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_DELETEFAIL:
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_ADDPARTFAIL:
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_oFCOPYMOVEFAIL:
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_SETCOMMENTFAIL:
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_CREATEDIRFAIL:
      case oFDH_HOOKSTAT_PATTERNFAIL:
      default:
        return( oFDH_HOOK_RETURN_SKIP );
    }

    return( oFDH_HOOK_RETURN_OK );
  }

  void main( void )
  {
    if( OpenUtilBase = (struct OpenUtilLibrary *)OpenLibrary( OPENUTILNAME, 2L ))
    {
      struct Hook AppHook  = { { NULL, NULL }, (VOID *)AppHookFunc, NULL, NULL };
      APTR        MainPool = CreatePool( MEMF_PUBLIC | MEMF_CLEAR, 8192UL, 1024UL );

      //oFDH_ACTION_Move:

      Result = oFileDirHandle( "Sys:T/",
                               "Sys:Temp/1/2/3/4",
                               oFDH_Action,          oFDH_ACTION_MOVE,
                               oFDH_FileCount,       (ULONG)&FileCount,
                               oFDH_ByteCount,       (ULONG)&ByteCount,
                               oFDH_DirCount,        (ULONG)&DirCount,
                               oFDH_Recursive,       TRUE,
                               oFDH_MaxCopyBuffer,   1048576UL,
                               oFDH_ForceDelete,     TRUE,
                               oFDH_MemoryPool,      (ULONG)MainPool, // If NULL systems memory will be used.
                               oFDH_StatusHook,      (ULONG)&AppHook,
                               oFDH_oFCopyMoveFlags, oFCMF_KEEPINFO | oFCMF_REPLACE | oFCMF_FORCE,
                               oFDH_Pattern,         (ULONG)"#?.info",
                               oFDH_CreateSubDirs,   TRUE,
                               // oFDH_StatusHookUserData, MyData,
                               TAG_DONE );

      if( MainPool )
      {
        DeletePool( MainPool );
      }

      CloseLibrary( (struct Library *)OpenUtilBase );
    }
  }
@endnode
@node oFileSize "OpenUtil.library / File Operations / oFileSize()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oFileSize -- Get the byte size of a file.

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oFileSize (Name)
                    A0

        long oFileSize (STRPTR)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function returns the byte size of the passed file.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Name         - Full AmigaDOS file name.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Size         - File size or -1 in the case of an error. Use IoErr()
                       to get an error code.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        David 'Strider/tRSi' Wettig (strider@trsi.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{"oExists()" link "oExists"}, @{"oGetProtection()" link "oGetProtection"}
@endnode
@node oFileToListA "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oFileToListA()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oFileToListA     -- load an Exec List from a file into memory
        oFileToList      -- varargs stub for oFileToListA()

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oFileToListA (File, Base, MemPool, WriteOffset, WriteSize, StructSize, TotalSize, Tags)
                       A0    A1      A2         D0          D1         D2          D3      A3

        oFileToList  (File, Base, MemPool, WriteOffset, WriteSize, StructSize, TotalSize, FirstTag, ...)

        long oFileToListA (BPTR, struct List *, void *, ULONG, ULONG, ULONG, ULONG, struct TagItem *)

        long oFileToList  (BPTR, struct List *, void *, ULONG, ULONG, ULONG, ULONG, Tag, ...)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function stocks up an Exec List with (additional) records (Nodes)
        as stored in a file using @{"oListToFileA()" link "oListToFileA"}.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        File            - A file handle with a current seek position at the
                          same point where @{"oListToFileA()" link "oListToFileA"} began to write.

        Base            - An Exec List which may either be empty or already
                          contain some Nodes. The new Nodes loaded from disk
                          get appended at the bottom (Tail) of the List.

        MemPool         - An Exec memory Pool which is used to allocate
                          all needed List Nodes. If NULL, the main system
                          memory is used instead.

        WriteOffset     - This value specifies the offset in a Node where
                          to copy the data to. WriteOffset must be at least
                          sizeof(struct Node). This is equal to the WriteOffset
                          value you've passed to @{"oListToFileA()" link "oListToFileA"}, so it has
                          the same name.

        WriteSize       - This is the stored byte size for one single List Node.
                          This value is equal to the WriteSize value passed to
                          @{"oListToFileA()" link "oListToFileA"}.

        StructSize      - The allocation size for each record. This is the size
                          of your structure including the List Node.

        TotalSize       - Overall read size for the List. This value is equal
                          to the result of the @{"oListToFileA()" link "oListToFileA"} call which wrote
                          the List. You may also partially load a list by
                          Seek()ing forward and passing a smaller TotalSize.

        Tags            - Optional. Currently, the following Tags are defined:

                          oFTL_Buffer

                            (APTR). A buffer is needed for buffered I/O
                            and should not be smaller than 32-64 KB; best
                            is 256 KB. If you already have a buffer, you
                            can pass it here, otherwise oFileToListA()
                            allocates one. Default: NULL.

                          oFTL_BufSize

                            (ULONG). This Tag sets the I/O buffer size.
                            Especially if you have passed an own buffer,
                            you may need to adjust the size here. If no
                            buffer is passed, this Tag changes the default
                            allocation size. Default: 256 KB.

                          oFTL_MsgWait

                            (struct oMsgWait *). If you're going to load very
                            large Lists (with more than some thousand entries
                            and/or more than a few MB file read size), you may
                            pass an oMsgWait structure here, as returned by
                            @{"oOpenMsgWaitA()" link "oOpenMsgWaitA"}. oFileToListA() will then update
                            the oMsgWait's Status Bar while reading the file.
                            Note that the passed oMsgWait structure should be
                            initialized with a MaxValue of approx. 50-5000,
                            not 500 million or other extreme values which
                            may overflow the progress display calculation.

                          oFTL_NodeNameOffset

                            Each Node gets allocated & initialized, which may also
                            include setting the ln_Name field. You may pass an
                            offset to a string which is stored inside each Node.
                            This offset must be >= sizeof(struct Node), of course.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Success           BOOL. If NULL, something went wrong. Call IoErr() for
                          more details then. After an error, the List comes back
                          as passed.

                          Note that the loaded nodes get appended at the bottom
                          (Tail) of the passed List. You may use @{"oClearList()" link "oClearList"}
                          to empty the List before calling oFileToListA().

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
        Please refer to the @{"oListToFileA()" link "oListToFileA"} autodoc example, which also includes
        an oFileToListA() usage example.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oListToFileA() " link "oListToFileA"}
@endnode
@node oFillMem "OpenUtil.library / Memory Functions / oFillMem()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oFillMem   -- Fill a memory block with a specific value

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oFillMem (Buffer, Value, Size)
                    A0      D0    D1

        APTR oFillMem (APTR, ULONG, ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function fills a memory block with a given LONG value.
        For filling with non-LONG values see below.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Buffer     - The Buffer to fill

        Value      - A LONG value to fill the Buffer with. If You want to
                     fill a memory block with null-bytes, you may also use
                     @{"oClearMem()" link "oClearMem"} instead.

                     To fill a buffer with a single byte value, for example,
                     with spaces, just pass '    ' here (0x20202020).

        Size       - Any byte size, which may also be odd. In this case, the
                     Buffer gets filled exactly up to the last byte. For example,
                     if you pass 'This' (0x54686973) as Value using a BufSize
                     of 11 bytes, the Buffer will contain "ThisThisThi".

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Buffer     - The passed Buffer, filled.

  @{b}NOTES@{ub}
        This function is dedicated to all the bigger buffers in the nation. :)

  @{b}BUGS@{ub}
        Due to function internal reasons, Size is currently limited to 13.631.280
        bytes, so if you're working with a Buffer larger than approx. 12MB, you'll
        need to call this function twice or several times.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oClearMem() " link "oClearMem"}
@endnode
@node oFormatVarStrA "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oFormatVarStrA()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oFormatVarStrA -- Format a free definable string with own buffers.
        oFormatVarStr  -- Varargs stub for oFormatVarStrA().

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oFormatVarStrA (SourceBuffer, DestBuffer, Tags)
                             A0           A1       A2

        oFormatVarStr  (SourceBuffer, DestBuffer, FirstTag, ...)

        STRPTR oFormatVarStrA (STRPTR, STRPTR, struct TagItem *)

        STRPTR oFormatVarStr  (STRPTR, STRPTR, Tag, ...)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        oFormatVarStrA() formats a string filled with variables by replacing
        the variables with different pre-defined string buffers which will be
        handed by tags to oFormatVarStrA(). The variables will be indicated
        by an '%' char followed by a value from '0' - '1', a char from
        'a' - 'z' or 'A' - 'Z' (case sensitive) what means that the function
        oFormatVarStrA() is able to handle 62 different variables.

        To handle the needed buffers for the variables you want to use with
        oFormatVarStrA() the following tag names will be used.

        The tag names will be named like this: oFVS_VarBuffer_<0-1;a-z;A-Z>

        Other additional tags:

        oFVS_KeepVar - If a variable is found, but not defined by a tag then
                       the variable will normally be removed. On using
                       oFVS_KeepVar the variable will be left intact.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        SourceBuffer - The format buffer which will be read to format.

        DestBuffer   - The buffer where the result will be written to.

        Tags         - Flags and all needed buffers to be formated.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        DestBuffer   - The same as DestBuffer from INPUTS.

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
        We want oFormatVarStrA() to be able to replace all '%N'
        variables handled over in SourceBuffer by the string:
        'Mr. Example'. To be able to do this we need to handle the
        following tag and tag data to oFormatVarStrA():

        ..., oFVS_VarBuffer_N, (ULONG)"Mr. Example", <...More tags...> );

        The following C source shows a second example:


        char Str1[ 256 ],
             Str2[ 256 ];

        struct TagItem MyTags[ 4 ];

        MyTags[ 0 ] . ti_Tag  = oFVS_VarBuffer_F;
        MyTags[ 0 ] . ti_Data = (ULONG)"FFF";
        MyTags[ 1 ] . ti_Tag  = oFVS_VarBuffer_W;
        MyTags[ 1 ] . ti_Data = (ULONG)"WWW";

        MyTags[ 2 ] . ti_Tag  = oFVS_KeepVar;
        MyTags[ 2 ] . ti_Data = TRUE;

        MyTags[ 3 ] . ti_Tag  = TAG_DONE;

        strcpy( Str1, "Hello % %you! %5.5F %X What %% is <%-5.5F%W%F%2.2W> <%F %W %F %W> going %W on???%" );

        Printf( "\n Original: <%s>\nConverted: <%s>\n\n", Str1, oFormatVarStrA( Str1, Str2, MyTags ));


        The visual result will be with oFVS_KeepVar = TRUE:

        Hello % %you! FFF %X What % is <FFFWWWFFFWWW> <FFF WWW FFF WWW> going WWW on???%

        And with oFVS_KeepVar = FALSE:

        Hello ou! FFF  What % is <FFFWWWFFFWWW> <FFF WWW FFF WWW> going WWW on???

  @{b}NOTES@{ub}
        Make sure your DestBuffer is big enough to receive the converted string.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        David 'Strider/tRSi' Wettig (strider@trsi.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oFormatVarStrRDFA() " link "oFormatVarStrRDFA"}
@endnode
@node oFormatVarStrRDFA "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oFormatVarStrRDFA()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oFormatVarStrRDFA -- Format a free definable string with own buffers.
        oFormatVarStrRDF  -- Varargs stub for oFormatVarStrRDFA().

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oFormatVarStrRDFA (SourceBuffer, DestBuffer, Tags)
                               A0            A1       A2

        oFormatVarStrRDF  (SourceBuffer, DestBuffer, FirstTag, ...)

        STRPTR oFormatVarStrRDFA (STRPTR, STRPTR, struct TagItem *)

        STRPTR oFormatVarStrRDF  (STRPTR, STRPTR, Tag, ...)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        oFormatVarStrRDFA() formats a string filled with variables by replacing
        the variables with different pre-defined string buffers which will be
        handed by tags to oFormatVarStrRDFA(). The variables will be indicated
        by an '%' char followed by a char from 'a' - 'z' or 'A' - 'Z'
        (case sensitive) what means that the function oFormatVarStrRDFA() is
        able to handle 52 different variables.

        oFormatVarStrRDFA() is using RawDoFmt() to format the buffer also with
        all RawDoFmt() possible flags like spacing, limiting, left formating...

        To handle the needed buffers for the variables you want to use with
        oFormatVarStrRDFA() the following tag names will be used.

        The tag names will be named like this: oFVS_VarBuffer_<a-z;A-Z>

        Other additional tags:

        oFVS_KeepVar - If a variable is found, but not defined by a tag then
                       the variable will normally be removed. On using
                       oFVS_KeepVar the variable will be left intact.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        SourceBuffer - The format buffer which will be read to format.

        DestBuffer   - The buffer where the result will be written to.

        Tags         - Flags and all needed buffers to be formated.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        DestBuffer   - The same as DestBuffer from INPUTS.

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
        We want oFormatVarStrRDFA() to be able to replace all '%N'
        variables handled over in SourceBuffer by the string:
        'Mr. Example'. To be able to do this we need to handle the
        following tag and tag data to oFormatVarStrRDFA():

        ..., oFVS_VarBuffer_N, (ULONG)"Mr. Example", <...More tags...> );

        The following C source shows a second example:


        char Str1[ 256 ],
             Str2[ 256 ];

        struct TagItem MyTags[ 4 ];

        MyTags[ 0 ] . ti_Tag  = oFVS_VarBuffer_F;
        MyTags[ 0 ] . ti_Data = (ULONG)"FFF";
        MyTags[ 1 ] . ti_Tag  = oFVS_VarBuffer_W;
        MyTags[ 1 ] . ti_Data = (ULONG)"WWW";

        MyTags[ 2 ] . ti_Tag  = oFVS_KeepVar;
        MyTags[ 2 ] . ti_Data = TRUE;

        MyTags[ 3 ] . ti_Tag  = TAG_DONE;

        strcpy( Str1, "Hello % %you! %5.5F %X What %% is <%-5.5F%W%F%2.2W> <%F %W %F %W> going %W on???%" );

        Printf( "\n Original: <%s>\nConverted: <%s>\n\n", Str1, oFormatVarStrRDFA( Str1, Str2, MyTags ));


        The visual result will be with oFVS_KeepVar = TRUE:

        Hello % %you! FFF %X What % is <FFFWWWFFFWWW> <FFF WWW FFF WWW> going WWW on???%

        And with oFVS_KeepVar = FALSE:

        Hello ou! FFF  What % is <FFFWWWFFFWWW> <FFF WWW FFF WWW> going WWW on???

  @{b}NOTES@{ub}
        Make sure your DestBuffer is big enough to receive the converted string.

        RDF (RawDoFmt) version is completely compatible to the simpler non RDF
        version.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        David 'Strider/tRSi' Wettig (strider@trsi.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oFormatVarStrA() " link "oFormatVarStrA"}
@endnode
@node oFreeDirInfo "OpenUtil.library / User Interface / oFreeDirInfo()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oFreeDirInfo -- free an oDirInfo object returned by @{"oBuildDirInfoA()" link "oBuildDirInfoA()"}

