  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Width           - Overall pixel width of the IntuiText.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oITextHeight() " link "oITextHeight"}, @{" oCreateITextChainA() " link "oCreateITextChainA"}
@endnode
@node oListIsEmpty "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oListIsEmpty()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oListIsEmpty -- Check if an Exec List is empty.

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oListIsEmpty (Base)
                       A0

        long oListIsEmpty (struct List *)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This one simply checks if a List is empty (or if there are Nodes linked).

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Base            - Exec List (may be NULL)

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        IsEmpty         - BOOL. TRUE, if the List is empty, or if Base is NULL.

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
        C:
                ULONG DoSomethingWithAList(struct List * Base)
                {
                  if (oListIsEmpty(Base))
                  {
                    return;
                  }
                  else
                  {
                    DoTheWorkOnTheValidList(Base);
                  }
                }

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oCountList() " link "oCountList"}
@endnode
@node oListToFileA "OpenUtil.library / List Functions / oListToFileA()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oListToFileA     -- write an Exec List to a file
        oListToFile      -- varargs stub for oListToFileA()

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oListToFileA (Base, File, WriteOffset, WriteSize, Tags)
                       A0    A1       D0           D1      A2

        oListToFile  (Base, File, WriteOffset, WriteSize, FirstTag, ...)

        ULONG oListToFileA (struct List *, BPTR, ULONG, ULONG, struct TagItem *)

        ULONG oListToFile  (struct List *, BPTR, ULONG, ULONG, Tag, ...)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        oListToFileA() writes the data part of each List Node into a file
        which can later get loaded back as Exec List using @{"oFileToListA()" link "oFileToListA"}.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Base            - An Exec List. If the List is empty, nothing
                          gets written.

        File            - A file handle which is opened with write access.
                          All List contents get appended at the current seek
                          position.

        WriteOffset     - An offset in each Record (List Node) where to start
                          saving data from. This offset must be at least
                          sizeof(struct Node), because there is no need to
                          save the Node structure to disk since it's allocated
                          and initialized by @{"oFileToListA()" link "oFileToListA"}.

        WriteSize       - This value specifies the data size for each Record
                          saved to disk. Refer to the example below.

        Tags            - Optional. The following Tags are currently defined:

                          oLTF_Buffer

                            (APTR). A buffer is needed for buffered I/O
                            and should not be smaller than 32-64 KB; best
                            is 256 KB. If you already have got a buffer,
                            you can pass it here, otherwise oListToFileA()
                            allocates one. Default: NULL.

                          oLTF_BufSize

                            (ULONG). This Tag sets the I/O buffer size.
                            Especially if you have passed an own buffer,
                            you may need to adjust the size here. If no
                            buffer is passed, this Tag changes the default
                            allocation size. Default: 256 KB.

                          oLTF_MsgWait

                            (struct oMsgWait *). If you're going to save very
                            large Lists (with more than some thousand entries
                            and/or more than a few MB file write size), you may
                            pass an oMsgWait structure here, as returned by
                            @{"oOpenMsgWaitA()" link "oOpenMsgWaitA"}. oListToFileA() will then update
                            the oMsgWait's Status Bar while writing the file.
                            Note that the passed oMsgWait structure should be
                            initialized with a MaxValue of approx. 50-5000,
                            not 500 millions or other extreme values which
                            may overflow the progress display calculation.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        BytesWritten    - ULONG. If NULL, something went wrong, which may be,
                          for example, ERROR_NO_FREE_STORE, ERROR_DISK_FULL,
                          ERROR_NO_MORE_ENTRIES (the passed List is empty)
                          and so on. If non-zero, everything went okay, where
                          Result always equals WriteSize * NumNodes.

                          For loading back the full list later, it's a good idea
                          to store BytesWritten and additional information about
                          the List in the same file. Since BytesWritten is a fixed
                          value which can easily be pre-calculated, you may write
                          a full data header at the begin the file before calling
                          oListToFileA().

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}

        C:
          // We already have an Exec memory Pool and an Exec List :

             void * MyPool;

             struct List * MyList;

          // MyList already contains some Records (Nodes) of the following type:

             struct MyRecord
             {
               struct Node ListNode;
               char   Name [40];
               ULONG  Number;
             }

          // We also have opened a file with write access:

             BPTR   MyFile;

          // Now let's save the List to disk. By the way: the WriteSize for our
          // example is 44 bytes: char Name[40] + ULONG Number = 44 bytes, which
          // is expressed below as: sizeof(struct MyRecord) - sizeof(struct Node)
          // in order to save the whole List. If your List Nodes contain temporary
          // data (like pointers to somewhere) which will change the next time
          // when loading back the List, you probably won't save all and everything.
          // Put such memory-only parts at the top and/or the bottom of your
          // structure and then let WriteOffset & WriteSize range only over the
          // middle data block which to write to disk.

             ULONG TotalSize;

             if (TotalSize = oListToFileA (MyList,
                                           MyFile,
                                           sizeof(struct Node),
                                           sizeof(struct MyRecord) - sizeof(struct Node),
                                           NULL))
             {
               oMsgInfo("Yahoo!","List saved.");
             }
             else
             {
               oMsgFault("File Error","Failed to save List");
             }

          // Now loading back the List. We let oFileToList() set the Node
          // names to &MyRecord->Name[0]. This fully prepares the List for
          // getting attached to a ListView Gadget later (which is not part
          // of the example).

             oClearList(MyList);  // we don't want to append

             if (oFileToList (MyFile,
                              MyList,
                              MyPool,
                              TotalSize,
                              sizeof(struct MyRecord),
                              sizeof(struct Node),
                              sizeof(struct MyRecord) - sizeof(struct Node),
                              oFTL_NodeNameOffset, sizeof(struct Node),
                              TAG_DONE))
             {
               oMsgInfo("Yahoo!","List loaded.");
             }
             else
             {
               oMsgFault("File Error","Failed to load List");
             }

  @{b}BUGS@{ub}
        In the case of a write error, oListToFileA() attempts to restore the
        original file size using SetFileSize(), which can also fail since some
        Handlers may not support this command. In this case, IoErr() will return
        the SetFileSize() error code after a fail. If SetFileSize() succeeded,
        IoErr() returns the write error code, which usually is ERROR_DISK_FULL.

  @{b}FUTURE@{ub}
        If future AmigaOS releases include a define for SetFileSize() fails,
        like ERROR_SETFILESIZE_ERROR, oListToFileA() will set IoErr to this
        value after a SetFileSize() fail.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oFileToListA() " link "oFileToListA"}
@endnode
@node oLoadFileA "OpenUtil.library / File Operations / oLoadFileA()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oLoadFileA       -- load a file into memory (V2)
        oLoadFile        -- varargs stub for oLoadFileA() (V2)

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oLoadFileA (FileName, Tags)
                       A0      A1

        oLoadFile  (FileName, FirstTag, ...)

        struct oMemFile * oLoadFileA (STRPTR, struct TagItem *)

        struct oMemFile * oLoadFile  (STRPTR, Tag, ...)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function loads a file into memory. The needed buffer gets allocated
        and returned to the caller, containing a filled FileInfoBlock structure,
        the file body and (optional) a shared Lock and a read access FileHandle.
        the oMemFile structure is currently only for use by your application;
        you won't need it again except freeing it back to memory.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        FileName        - Full AmigaDOS file name.

        Tags            - Currently, the following Tags are defined:

                          oLF_MemPool

                            For smaller files, an Exec memory Pool can be used
                            to allocate the buffer from. If not passed, the
                            buffer gets allocated from the System main memory.

                          oLF_MemAttrs

                            (ULONG). Only if not using oLF_MemPool, this Tag
                            is used to pass the needed Exec MemAttrs, like
                            MEMF_CHIP. Default: MEMF_PUBLIC.

                          oLF_KeepLock

                            (BOOL). If you need to hold the file Lock after
                            loading, pass TRUE in ti_Data. Then, the entry
                            oMemFile->Lock will contain a shared (read) Lock
                            instead of NULL. You'll need to UnLock() the file
                            yourself after setting this Tag to TRUE.
                            Default: FALSE.

                          oLF_KeepFH

                            (BOOL). Similar to oLF_KeepLock, this one passes
                            a shared (read) File Handle in oMemFile->FH instead
                            of NULL. You'll need to Close() the file yourself
                            after setting this Tag to TRUE. Default: FALSE.

                          oLF_Force

                            (BOOL). If TRUE, oLoadFile() will override read
                            protection by temporary changing the read protection
                            bit. Default: FALSE (fails if read protected).

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        oMemFile        struct oMemFile *. If NULL, something went wrong, which
                        can be many. IoErr() will return an error code then,
                        including all AmigaDOS Lock()/Examine()/Open()/Read()
                        error codes or either ERROR_NO_FREE_STORE if out of
                        memory or ERROR_NO_MORE_ENTRIES if the file is empty.

                        After done with the file, the oMemFile structure must get
                        freed back to memory using @{"oFreeVecPooled()" link "oFreeVecPooled"}.

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
        C:
          struct oMemFile * HomePage;

          if (HomePage = oLoadFileA("MyHomePage.html", 0))
          {
            MyDisplayHTML(HomePage->Body);

            oFreeVecPooled(HomePage);
          }
          else
          {
            oMsgFault("Error", "Failed to load HomePage");
          }

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oSaveFileA() " link "oSaveFileA"}, @{"oFreeVecPooled()" link "oFreeVecPooled"}
@endnode
@node oLoadPrefs "OpenUtil.library / Misc. Functions / oLoadPrefs()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oLoadPrefs       -- Custom function for loading application prefs (V2)

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oLoadPrefs (FileName, GroupID, SubID, DefaultPrefs, ObjectName, ObjectVerPtr, ObjectRevPtr)
                       A0        D0      D1        A1            A2          A3            D2

        long oLoadPrefs (STRPTR, ULONG, ULONG, struct TagItem *, STRPTR, ULONG *, ULONG *)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This is a specialized custom function used to easily load a preferences
        file. @{"oSavePrefs()" link "oSavePrefs"} can be used to create such files.

        Let me try a description: oLoadPrefs() equips a passed data structure
        with data loaded from to disk. This function is more simple than it
        looks at first sight and offers the following features:

        You can remove obsolete or add new fields to your structure when releasing
        program updates without needing any preferences file conversion. You may
        also change the order of presence in your structure; any already existing
        prefs file will stay up- and downward compatible because oLoadPrefs()
        equips your structure variable-by-variable using descriptor Tags each
        item. For using oLoadPrefs() / @{"oSavePrefs()" link "oSavePrefs"}, you won't need to do any
        changes to an existing program except redefinition of the data structure
        which to save to / load from disk.

        The preferences files (created using @{"oSavePrefs()" link "oSavePrefs"}) are saved in IFF format
        including a standard IFF Prefs header (PRHD). @{"oSavePrefs()" link "oSavePrefs"} also adds a
        32Bit data CRC checksum to the file. oLoadPrefs() always checks file type
        and data integrity.

        Please refer to the example below for further details.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        FileName      - Full AmigaDOS file name. This file must have been
                        created using @{"oSavePrefs()" link "oSavePrefs"}, else oLoadPrefs()
                        rejects the call with an error.

        GroupID       - An IFF chunk ID to use for your application. It consists
                        of four ASCII characters; IFF chunk IDs must follow the
                        IFF 85 Chunk ID specification, else oLoadPrefs() will
                        reject the call with an error. If you're not sure,
                        GoodID() (iffparse.library) will help.

        SubID         - Another IFF chunk ID used to specify a sub file type.
                        Even if you need to split prefs into several files, you
                        only need one GroupID; then you can freely define millions
                        of private IDs (which must also follow the IFF guidelines),
                        one each file type. Companies or developer groups may
                        use their abbrev. as GroupID and own defined sub IDs
                        for all their projects, however. Both GroupID and SubID
                        must be valid, else oLoadPrefs() returns an error.

        DefaultPrefs  - A pointer to your prefs structure, already set up with
                        default settings for use for the case that the prefs file
                        isn't present or only contains partial information, like
                        files created using older application versions.

        ObjectName    - This one points to a char buffer which shall receive the
                        name for the prefs object (file) which was used for the
                        "$VER: .." version string. If you don't need the name,
                        pass NULL here. A passed buffer must have a size of
                        at least 32 bytes.

        ObjectVerPtr  - A @{b}pointer@{ub} to a ULONG which receives the version number of
                        the file. If you don't need it, pass NULL here.

        ObjectRevPtr  - A @{b}pointer@{ub} to a ULONG which receives the revision number
                        of the file. If you don't need it, pass NULL here.
                        Asm programmers note that D2 is used here, not A4 or A5.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Success       - BOOL. If TRUE, everything was successfully loaded.

                        If FALSE, IoErr() will return an error code, which
                        may also be NULL, which means that some requested entries
                        were not found in the file, staying unchanged in the
                        passed prefs structure. This will happen if a user runs a
                        new update of your application the first time. You may
                        use this to let the user know that there's something new.
                        This won't occur again after the next @{"oSavePrefs()" link "oSavePrefs"} call,
                        which always builds new prefs files from scratch.

                        The passed prefs structure always gets stocked up with
                        the contents of the passed prefs file as far as possible.
                        Even after an error, your passed prefs structure will
                        only contain valid entries since you've passed it filled
                        with valid defaults.

                        If Result = FALSE and IoErr() returns a non-zero Error
                        Code, something went wrong and the passed prefs structure
                        comes back as passed.

                        oLoadPrefs() uses the following additional IoErr() codes
                        for special errors:

                        ERROR_OBJECT_WRONG_TYPE
                          The prefs file is of wrong file type. Either it's
                          of wrong file type or the file CRC check failed.

                        ERROR_BAD_HUNK
                          This one should only appear in the application
                          development phase, where oLoadPrefs() has detected
                          an item in the prefs file with the same ID as one of
                          the Tags in the passed prefs structure, but with a
                          different size.
                          Refer to the notes below which explain how to avoid
                          this Error Code in general. In the case of this error,
                          oLoadPrefs() just breaks at the element which failed.

                        ERROR_INVALID_COMPONENT_NAME
                          Also an error which normaly doesn't happen: you've
                          passed an illegal GroupID or SubID. Use GoodID()
                          (iffparse.library) once to check if an ID is okay.

                          Currently, GroupID and SubID are not used as Chunk IDs
                          (they are stored inside the oPRF Chunk), but this may
                          well change in the future.

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}
        C:
          // first: a default example without oLoadPrefs()/oSavePrefs() calls:

          // example prefs structure definition

          struct MyPrefs
          {
            ULONG  TaskPriority;
            char   RecentFileName[256];
            struct timeval AutoSaveInterval;
            UBYTE  AppFlags;
          };

          // example AppFlag

          #define MYAPPFF_ASKQUIT (1L<<0) // let a user confirm quit (by default)

          // now our prefs structure in memory

          struct MyPrefs ProgramPrefs;

          // static default prefs, used if a prefs file isn't present

          struct MyPrefs DefaultPrefs =
          {
            0,                  // TaskPri: standard
            {0},                // no recent project
            {15*60,0}           // autosave every 15 mins
            MYAPPFF_ASKQUIT;    // popup requester on quit
          };

          // Init default prefs: copying the defaults to our memory prefs structure

          CopyMem(&DefaultPrefs, &ProgramPrefs, sizeof(struct MyPrefs));

          if (!(MyLoadPrefs("PROGDIR:Config/MyPrg.prefs",
                            &ProgramPrefs))
          {
            oMsgInfo("File Error", "Failed to load prefs (using defaults)");
          }

          // simplified quit handle. Used to show how a prefs item is
          // accessed. This is exactly the same as in the new example below.

          if (ProgramPrefs.AppFlags & MYAPPFF_ASKQUIT)
          {
            while (!(oMsgYesNo("Quit", "Quit Program ?")))
            {}
          }
          return();


          /*
            Now the same thing converted for use with oLoadPrefs() / @{"oSavePrefs()" link "oSavePrefs"};
            all items just get a TagItem attached at the top, defining type and
            size (ti_Tag/ti_Data) for each item. Since this is not defined as
            embedded sub structure, you won't need to change your code where
            accessing your prefs structure. You may freely choose all Tag names;
            the Tags don't get used by your application beyond defining them:
          */

          #include <libraries/iffparse.h>       // contains the MAKE_ID() macro

          struct MyPrefs
          {
            //             any Tag name         Contents as defined above

            struct TagItem PT_TaskPriority;     ULONG  TaskPriority;
            struct TagItem PT_RecentFileName;   char   RecentFileName[256];
            struct TagItem PT_AutoSaveInterval; struct timeval AutoSaveInterval;
            struct TagItem PT_AppFlags;         UBYTE  AppFlags;
          };

          #define MYAPPFF_ASKQUIT (1L<<0)

          // Now we define the (unique) item IDs for our Prefs structure:

          #define MyID_TaskPriority     1
          #define MyID_RecentFileName   2
          #define MyID_AutoSaveInterval 3
          #define MyID_AppFlags         4

          struct MyPrefs ProgramPrefs;    // our preferences

          // now the new default prefs structure. To the right there are
          // the entries as defined in the example above:

          struct MyPrefs DefaultPrefs =   // static defaults
          {
            // Entry ID (ti_Tag)    Entry Size (ti_Data)     Entry Data (as defined)

            {MyID_TaskPriority,     sizeof(ULONG)},          0,
            {MyID_RecentFileName,   sizeof(char[256])},      {0},
            {MyID_AutoSaveInterval, sizeof(struct TimeVal)}, {15*60,0},
            {MyID_AppFlags,         sizeof(UBYTE)},          MYAPPFF_ASKQUIT,
            TAG_DONE             // termination
          };

          CopyMem(&DefaultPrefs, &ProgramPrefs, sizeof(struct MyPrefs)); // as above

          if (!(oLoadPrefs("PROGDIR:Config/MyPrg.prefs",
                           MAKE_ID('M','Y','A','P'),    // "MYAP" (Application ID)
                           MAKE_ID('M','A','I','N'),    // "MAIN" (My main prefs ID)
                           &ProgramPrefs,
                           0, 0, 0)))                   //  ObjectName/Version/Revision not needed
          {
            if (IoErr)
            {
              oMsgFault("File Error", "Failed to load prefs (using defaults)");
            }
            else
            {
              oMsgInfo("New Version", "Welcome to the new update !");
            }
          }

          // accessing our ProgramPrefs.Appflags. As stated above,
          // this is still the same:

          if (ProgramPrefs.AppFlags & MYAPPFF_ASKQUIT)
          {
            while (!(oMsgYesNo("Quit", "Quit Program ?")))
            {}
          }
          return();

  @{b}NOTES@{ub}
        The only caveeat is that you may not re-define obsolete Tag IDs for
        use with new entries, else oLoadPrefs() will equip your prefs structure
        with wrong data (if both old and new size definitions are equal, too).

        To avoid such collisions, best use incremental Tag IDs. You may of
        course specify identical IDs for different file types as long as not
        both GroupID and SubID are equal. The Tags within the prefs structure
        passed to oLoadPrefs() / @{"oSavePrefs()" link "oSavePrefs"} are used because they are handy
        for it, but they are handled different from the common TagItem array
        model and they aren't used with AmigaOS Tag functions, so there are
        no external restrictions, like the usual need to add "TAG_USER" to
        ti_Tag; you can use any ULONG value there.

        Even if OpenUtil.library uses 68020+ only, all TagItems must be aligned
        to an even address; C compilers align such things by default, while Asm
        programmers need to add a pad-byte after each odd-sized entry.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oSavePrefs() " link "oSavePrefs"}
@endnode
@node oLockWindow "OpenUtil.library / User Interface / oLockWindow()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oLockWindow      -- Disable user input in a Window

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oLockWindow (Window)
                       A0

        struct oWindowLock * oLockWindow (struct Window *)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function disables all user input in the passed Window, including
        Window resizing. All Window IDCMP messaging is turned off; the Window's
        Mouse Pointer changes to a busy-wait Pointer. Even if synchronous
        Windowing is not the latest fashion in development, this function can
        be useful when opening a Requester or a sub Window which to close first
        before going on.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Window          - A valid, opened Window which to disable. May be NULL.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        WindowLock      (struct oWindowLock *). An oWindowLock structure containing
                        all information for unlocking, or NULL if out of memory.
                        IoErr() will return ERROR_NO_FREE_STORE then. To unlock
                        the Window, pass the oWindowLock to @{"oUnlockWindow()" link "oUnlockWindow"}.

  @{b}NOTES@{ub}
        Before you can close a locked Window , you *must* call @{"oUnlockWindow()" linl "oUnlockWindow"}
        first, otherwise @{"oUnlockWindow()" link "oUnlockWindow"} accesses a non-existing Window !

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oUnlockWindow() " link "oUnlockWindow"}
@endnode
@node oLTrim "OpenUtil.library / String Functions / oLTrim()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oLTrim     -- Strip leading TAB and SPACE chars from a string

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oLTrim (String)
                  A0

        STRPTR oLTrim (STRPTR)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function removes all TAB and SPACE characters from the left side
        of a given string.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        String     - The string to trim

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        String     - The modified string (equal to input)

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oRTrim() " link "oRTrim"}, @{" oAllTrim() " link "oAllTrim"}
@endnode
@node oMakePath "OpenUtil.library / File Operations / oMakePath()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oMakePath -- Make sure that a path including all sub dirs exists (V2)

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oMakePath (Path, Flags)
                    A0    D0

        long oMakePath (STRPTR, ULONG)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        If you have a string describing a path with various sub paths which
        are not existsing or only in parts you can use oMakePath()
        to let all these paths be created in one go without breaking if
        a directory already exists.

        Unlike @{"oCreatePath()" link "oCreatePath"} you will only get TRUE for success or FALSE
        for a failure as result and no lock.
        The main difference between both functions is that oMakePath()
        does not fail if the directory to be created already exists.

        So oMakePath() is more to make sure a path exists anyway.

        You need to use oCPFF_CREATESUBDIRS as a Flag to enable the sub directory
        creation feature. Without oCPFF_CREATESUBDIRS oMakePath() works 
        like CreateDir() from dos.library and creates only a single directory.

  @{b}NOTE@{ub}
        oMakePath() is internally the same as calling @{"oCreatePath()" link "oCreatePath"}
        with oCPFF_CREATESUBDIRS and oCPFF_OVERRIDEEXISTS as flags, except
        of no need to unlock the locked directory if oMakePath()
        returns. So if you need to be sure that you are the first exclusive
        owner of the new created directory don't use oMakePath(),
        but @{"oCreatePath()" link "oCreatePath"} with oCDF_CREATESUBDIRS and oCPFF_OVERRIDEEXISTS
        as flags.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Name         - The string describing a chain of directories to be created.

        Flags        - oCDF_CREATESUBDIRS to enable the creation of all non-
                       existing sub directories.

                     - oCPFF_OVERRIDEEXISTS has not to be set, because
                       oMakePath() does that for you.

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        DirLock      - NULL if something fails, else a lock to the last created
                       directory (the requested one).

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        David 'Strider/tRSi' Wettig (strider@trsi.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oCreatePath() " link "oCreatePath"}
@endnode
@node oMatch "OpenUtil.library / Internal Functions / oMatch()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oMatch       -- Check data for matching / being equal

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oMatch (Object, Mode, Case, With)
                  A0     D0    D1    A1

        ULONG oMatch (APTR, ULONG, ULONG, APTR)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This is more an internal function which is used by some OpenUtil functions
        which offer to compare multiple types of data. If a match mode is given
        from outside (the caller), such functions don't need to contain always
        the same case expression.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        Object          - Something which to compare with With. For example,
                          if you scan a List for matches, each data entry is
                          passed as Object. This value is defined as APTR,
                          but gets used together with the several Match Modes
                          as UBYTE, UWORD, ULONG, QUADWORD ptr, STRPTR or AmigaDOS
                          Pattern string. C programmers will need type casting.

        Mode            - Match Mode. Object can be compared with With using
                          one of the following Modes:

                          oMATCHMODE_Byte

                            Object & Mode are BYTE/UBYTE.

                            Match condition: Object == With.

                          oMATCHMODE_Word

                            Object & Mode are WORD/UWORD.

                            Match condition: Object == With.

                          oMATCHMODE_Long

                            Object & Mode are LONG/ULONG.

                            Match condition: Object == With.

                          oMATCHMODE_QuadPtr

                            Object & Mode are QUADWORD (64-bit value) pointers.

                            Since MC680x0 isn't a 64-bit CPU, oMATCHMODE_QuadPtr
                            sets Object & With type to ULONG *. The first ULONG
                            is the upper half of the 64-bit number, the second
                            ULONG is the lower one.

                            Match condition: Object == With.

                          oMATCHMODE_StrBegin

                          - Object & Mode are strings (STRPTR).

                            Match condition: Object begins with With.

                          oMATCHMODE_StrEnd

                          - Object & Mode are strings (STRPTR).

                            Match condition: Object ends with With.

                          oMATCHMODE_StrAny

                            Object & With are strings (STRPTR).

                            Match condition: Object contains With at any position.

                          oMATCHMODE_StrExact

                            Object & With are strings (STRPTR).

                            Match condition: Object is equal to With.

                          oMATCHMODE_StrPattern

                            Object is a string (STRPTR), With is an AmigaDOS
                            pattern string, as returned by ParsePattern().
                            Provide at least 1500 bytes of Stack space when
                            using this one.

                            Match condition: Object matches with Width.

        Case            - BOOL. TRUE = case sensitive. Ignored if not using
                          one of the oMATCHMODE_StrXxxx Modes.

        With            - This is the search (or match) expression (value)
                          which is compared with (the several) Object(s). This
                          can be UBYTE, UWORD, ULONG, QUADWORD ptr or STRPTR,
                          including AmigaDOS Pattern strings, as created by
                          dos.library/ParsePattern().

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Match           - NULL if Object doesn't match with With.

                          Attention: If not NULL, Result can be anything
                          different, so don't compare with TRUE.

                          When using oMATCHMODE_StrPattern, note that oMatch()
                          calls dos.library/MatchPattern(), which checks for
                          Stack overflows. If oMatch() returns FALSE, check
                          IoErr(), which may be NULL (okay but no match) or
                          (for example) ERROR_TOO_MANY_LEVELS.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)
@endnode
@node oMsgConfirmA "OpenUtil.library / User Interface / oMsgConfirmA()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oMsgConfirmA -- Open a requester offering "Yes", "No" or "Cancel"
        oMsgConfirm  -- varargs stub for oMsgConfirmA()

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oMsgConfirmA (TitleText, BodyText, Argv)
                          A0        A1      A2

        oMsgConfirm  (TitleText, BodyText, ...)

        long oMsgConfirmA (STRPTR, STRPTR, long *)

        long oMsgConfirm  (STRPTR, STRPTR, ...)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function opens a requester displaying the passed text and offers
        "Yes", "No" or "Cancel" as user answer.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        TitleText       - Requester Window title text or NULL (use default text)

        BodyText        - Window body text. The overall length of BodyText
                          @{B}after@{ub} RawDoFmt() is limited to 4096 Bytes.

        Argv            - RawDoFmt() args for BodyText

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Answer            1 if user answered "Yes"

                       NULL if user answered "No"

                         -1 if user answered "Cancel"

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}

        C:
                long UserAnswer;

                UserAnswer = oMsgConfirm("Quit","Save Changes ?");

                if (UserAnswer == 1)
                {
                  MySaveChanges();
                }
                if (UserAnswer != -1)
                {
                  MyQuit();
                }
                Printf("Let's continue..");

  @{b}FUTURE@{ub}
        Currently, this function uses EasyRequestArgs(), which is subject to
        replace by a more flexible workaround.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oMsgFaultA() " link "oMsgFaultA"}, @{" oMsgInfoA() " link "oMsgInfoA"},
        @{" oMsgYesNoA() " link "oMsgYesNoA"}, @{" oOpenMsgWaitA() " link "oOpenMsgWaitA"}
@endnode
@node oMsgFaultA "OpenUtil.library / User Interface / oMsgFaultA()"

  @{b}NAME@{ub}
        oMsgFaultA -- Open a requester displaying an AmigaDOS error message
        oMsgFault  -- varargs stub for oMsgFaultA()

  @{b}SYNOPSIS@{ub}
        oMsgFaultA (TitleText, BodyText, Argv)
                        A0        A1      A2

        oMsgFault  (TitleText, BodyText, ...)

        long oMsgFaultA (STRPTR, STRPTR, long *)

        long oMsgFault  (STRPTR, STRPTR, ...)

  @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
        This function opens a requester displaying the passed text including
        the Fault() string of the last AmigaDOS error code in brackets at the
        bottom of the passed BodyText.

  @{b}INPUTS@{ub}
        TitleText       - Requester Window title text or NULL (use default text)

        BodyText        - Window body text. The overall length of BodyText
                          @{B}after@{ub} RawDoFmt() is limited to 4096 Bytes.

        Argv            - RawDoFmt() args for BodyText

  @{b}RESULT@{ub}
        Success           BOOL. NULL if out of memory.

  @{b}EXAMPLE@{ub}

        C:
                STRPTR FileName = "AFileWhichDoesNotExist";

                if (!(Open(FileName,MODE_OLDFILE)))
                {
                  oMsgFault("Error","Can't open %s",FileName);
                }

  @{b}FUTURE@{ub}
        Currently, this function uses EasyRequestArgs(), which is subject to
        replace by a more flexible workaround.

  @{b}AUTHOR@{ub}
        Oliver "Bloodrock/tRSi" Lange (bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de)

  @{b}SEE ALSO@{ub}
        @{" oMsgConfirmA() " link "oMsgConfirmA"}, @{" oMsgInfoA() " link "oMsgInfoA"},
        @{" oMsgYesNoA() " link "oMsgYesNoA"}, @{" oOpenMsgWaitA() " link "oOpenMsgWaitA"}
@endnode
