@node GeneralNotes "OpenUtil.library / Notes / General"

                              General Notes
                              -------------

If not stated otherwise, OpenUtil.library functions require less than 1000 bytes
of Stack space. This doesn't include the Stack used by system functions called
by an OpenUtil function. However, a program Stack size of 8192 bytes should fit
all needs.

Everything related to OpenUtil.library which is declared as obsolete will be
*removed* after a delay of two years.
@endnode
@node GUINotes "OpenUtil.library / Notes / GUI"

                                GUI Notes
                                ---------

When OpenUtil.library opens a Request kind Window (like oMsgInfoA()), the Window
is opened with the default answer Button placed under the Mouse Pointer, or
at least centered in the middle of the Screen. If ThisTask->pr_WindowPtr is
valid, the Window is opened on that Window's Screen, else on the default
Public Screen.

Currently, most oMsgXXX() functions use EasyRequestArgs(), so RTPatch should
be installed to have the Windows centered in Screen or placed under the Mouse
Pointer. This is subject to change.
@endnode
@node ListFunctionNotes "OpenUtil.library / Notes / List Functions"

                           List Function Notes
                           -------------------

1. OpenUtil.library List functions always except Exec Lists.

   When working on free Node chains (structures containing at least an embedded
   struct Node), @{"oAddExecHeader()" link "oAddExecHeader"} and @{"oRemExecHeader()" link "oRemExecHeader"} are handy for
   easily converting Node chains to Exec Lists and vice versa.

2. OpenUtil.library List functions support Exec memory Pools.

   Allocating many small things goes much faster & better when allocated from
   standalone Exec memory Pools instead of the main system memory.
   Since OpenUtil.library always requires AmigaOS 3.0, simply let Exec create
   a memory Pool for you and then pass it to the needed List function(s)
   instead of NULL (which would allocate from the system main memory instead).
   If you haven't used Exec Pools yet, some typical example values below:

   MemFlags:   as needed for later allocations from the Pool.
   PuddleSize: approx. 32K - 128K
   TreshSize:  approx.  4K -  16K (must be smaller than (PuddleSize-16).

3. All OpenUtil functions which may free ressources back to memory always use
   @{"oFreeVecPooled()" link "oFreeVecPooled"} therefor. So all Nodes in that List must have been
   allocated using @{"oAllocVecPooledA()" link "oAllocVecPooledA"} or any other OpenUtil function.
@endnode
@node MemoryNotes "OpenUtil.library / Notes / Memory"

                              Memory Notes
                              ------------

Some OpenUtil.library functions allocate memory ressources for you, like List
Nodes when loading a List from disk. If there is no additional function stated
for freeing such ressources, oFreeVecPooled(Object) is the answer.

All OpenUtil.library functions which must allocate memory use @{"oAllocVecPooledA()" link "oAllocVecPooledA"}
therefor, which can be used on both system main memory and private Exec Pools.
@{"oFreeVecPooled()" link "oFreeVecPooled"} always requires only one argument - the address.
@endnode
@node StringCaseNotes "OpenUtil.library / Notes / String Case Sensitivity"
@next oAddU64

                              String Case Sensitivity
                              -----------------------

Wherever OpenUtil.library offers non-case-sensitive string handling, the used
case translation table is OpenUtilBase->ou_UpperCaseTable, which also considers
all special characters, like german "Umlauts".
@endnode
@node Introduction "OpenUtil.Guide: Introduction"
@next oAddU64
@prev Main

                   Welcome to OpenUtil.library !
                   -----------------------------

OpenUtil.library is a public shared function Library which contains anything
which came in mind worth put into a Library. It's a container for everything
me and others might need, and there's no restriction for function class & kind.

Some functions are just simple replacements for some common ANSI-C functions,
other functions are AmigaOS add-ons, and more. Just have a look at the function
descriptions in this documentation.


System Requirements
-------------------

OpenUtil.library requires AmigaOS 3.0+ and at least a 68020 CPU.

The future of our Amiga is unstable as never before. Everybody has nice
ideas, but nothing special happened yet. Very hard for Amiga programmers
to write future compatible applications if nobody knows what's coming up.

Let's wait'n see how OpenUtil.library could be integrated in the future,
if there's one. Some functions may then of course be obsolete. In order
not to overload this library with tons of obsolete functions, there's a
special rule coming with this library: everything related to OpenUtil.library
which gets declared as obsolete will be REMOVED after a delay of two years.


Usage
-----

OpenUtil.library works like most other Amiga Libraries and needs the following
lines added to your source code in order to include all needed OpenUtil stuff:

        C:
        --
                #include <proto/OpenUtil.h>
                #include <libraries/OpenUtil.h>

        Asm:
        ----

                INCLUDE  "libraries/OpenUtil.i"
                INCLUDE  "libraries/OpenUtil_lib.i"

After a successful OpenLibrary(OPENUTILNAME,OPENUTILVERSION) it's ready for use.

Note: OpenUtilBase holds a total of 19 Library Bases ready for use with your
application; no need to open & close all the Libs. SAS/C programmers may
link with the supplied (optimized) startup module "cres_OpenUtil.o" instead
of "cres.o", reducing code size while supplying the 19 Libs instead of ANSI-C.:)

If OpenUtil.library fails to open, a failure requester appears and informs
about the reason. The requester will not pop up on AmigaOS before 2.0.


Shareware
---------

PD and FreeWare applications which use OpenUtil.library don't need any
registration and may use OpenUtil.library for free. Just release it.

Commercial applications (including ShareWare) must be registered for using
OpenUtil.library by sending one free & fully registered copy to:
<bloodrock@bloody.in-berlin.de> (If you do not trust in sending data over
InterNet, just contact me first). This includes all future updates if
still using OpenUtil.library. However, there's no need to pay money for
using OpenUtil.library.

Since OpenUtil.library may contain functions written by other developers,
it was always a good deed if you'd also send registered copies to the authors
of the other OpenUtil functions used by your program.

CD distributors just send free CDs of your releases / series / collections
containing OpenUtil.library.

Beyond that, OpenUtil.library may be used & spread anywhere, as long as no
profit is made by selling it, and as long as at least OpenUtil.library and
it's documentaion stays unmodified (except packing / encrypting, of course).
The original OpenUtil.library releases can be downloaded from AmiNet,
path: util/libs/OpenULxx.lha (where xx stands for the Version number).

Because you do not pay anything for using OpenUtil.library, i do not pay
anything for problems caused by using OpenUtil.library. Same goes for all
other authors who wrote OpenUtil.library functions. OpenUtil.library shall
just help other Amiga developers saving some time (and money).

OpenUtil.library is always used at *own risk*.

If you find bugs, however, please tell me.


